It was not until after I started swinning that I noticed the eurrent was
so strong. I estimated it later at about four or five nots. As I was
progressing toward shore several Japanese planes dived on me and machine-gunned
ше.
At first I submerged nyself when they started shooting, but later beesme
so exhausted I could not do this. Many bullets caneextremely close so close
in fact that it left no doubt as to whether they were aiming at me or the
ship. After what seened an endless time, I resched the shore in a state of
complete exhaustion. I was umble to raise myself out of the water for
some time.
Either at the time I resched shore or at the time I finally pulled myself
completely out of the water, I saw the Douglas a considerable distance down
stream, half submerged, floating in a nose-down position. I believe it was
at this time I looked at my watch and ascertained the time to be 8:50 a.m.
It was probably over an hour before I could stand.
I was violently 11l
at my stomach.
As soon as I gathered sufficient strength, I started walking along the
bank of the river in the direction the plane hed disappeared.
After walking
approximately a half mile, I came upon a soldier and was led to where another
group of soldiers were located. Both the soldiers and myself were trying to
get information, but as they spoke no English I spoke no Chinese, were unsuccess-
ful.
Even at this time the Japanese planes were still in the vicinity. Just
when they stopped machine-gunning the plane and myself, I an not sure.
After mmerous unsuecessful attempts on the part of the soldiers and
myself to comminicate, I was put into a saall fishing boat, accompenied by one
soldier, and proceeded with the current into the interior. I understand this
was a tidal current that was flowing.
We rode for more than an hour and finally landed at a smell village.
